{"title_page": "Steven H Silver", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| image          = Steven_H_Silver.jpg\n| image_size     = 150px |\n| caption        = Silver in 2008\n| subject name   = Steven H Silver\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1967|4|19}}\n| birth_place    = [[Hinsdale, Illinois]], United States \n| occupation     = [[Technical writer]], [[editing|editor]], [[publisher]], [[reviewer]], bid proposal writer\n}}\n'''Steven H <!-- no punctuation point after the \"H\" -->Silver''' (born April 19, 1967) is an [[United States|American]] [[science fiction]] [[science fiction fandom|fan]] and [[bibliography|bibliographer]], publisher, author, and [[List of science fiction editors|editor]].  He has been nominated for the [[Hugo Award]] for [[Hugo Award for Best Fan Writer|Best Fan Writer]] twelve times and [[Hugo Award for Best Fanzine|Best Fanzine]] five times without winning.<ref name=\"Locus\">{{cite web|last=Kelly |first=Mark R. |title=Hugo Nominees List |work=Locus Index to SF Awards |publisher=Locus |year=2009 |url=http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/HugoNomList.html |access-date=2009-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110920202744/http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/HugoNomList.html |archive-date=September 20, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Editor, publisher, and writer==\nSilver was born in [[Hinsdale, Illinois]]. He is a longtime contributing editor to [[SF Site]] and has written that site's news page since its inception.\n\nIn 2003, he co-edited three anthologies with [[Martin H. Greenberg]], ''[[Wondrous Beginnings]]'', ''[[Magical Beginnings]]'', and ''[[Horrible Beginnings]]'', which reprinted the first published stories of authors in the [[science fiction]], [[fantasy]], and [[Horror fiction|horror]] genres. From 2004 through 2012 he was the publisher and editor of [[ISFiC Press]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Silver Resigns from ISFiC Press | publisher = SF Site | date = 2012-11-12 | url = http://www.sfsite.com/news/2012/11/12/silver-resigns-from-isfic-press/ | accessdate = 2012-11-16}}</ref>\n\nSilver published his first short story, \"''Les Lettres de Paston''\", in the final issue of ''[[Helix SF]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Silver | first = Steven H | title = Les Lettres de Paston | journal = Helix SF | issue = 10 | date = Fall 2008 | url = http://www.sfsite.com/~silverag/les_lettres_de_paston.htm | accessdate = 2008-10-01}}</ref> Silver had earlier written a column on [[alternate history]] for the magazine.\n\nIn 2009 and 2010, he edited the two volume Selected Stories of [[Lester del Rey]] for [[NESFA Press]].  The first volume is entitled ''War and Space'' and appeared in August, 2009.<ref>{{cite web | title = War and Space by Lester del Rey | publisher = NESFA Press | date = December 12, 2009 | url = http://www.nesfa.org/press/Books/delRey-1.html | accessdate = March 16, 2010}}</ref> The second volume, ''Robots and Magic'' was published in February 2010.<ref>{{cite web | title = Magic and Robots by Lester del Rey | publisher = NESFA Press | date = December 12, 2009 | url = http://www.nesfa.org/press/Books/delRey-2.html | accessdate = March 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Fandom==\n\n===Sidewise and Nebula Awards===\nIn 1995, he founded the [[Sidewise Award for Alternate History]] and has served as a judge ever since.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uchronia.net/sidewise/about.html |title=Sidewise: About the Awards |publisher=Uchronia.net |date= |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref> He was on the short story jury for the [[Nebula Award]] in 2002,<ref>''SFWA Forum'', February 2003, p. 10</ref> and on the novel jury for the Nebula Award in 2003,<ref>''SFWA Forum'', April 2003, p. 15</ref> 2006,<ref>[http://www.sfwa.org/org/voluntrs.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060924223240/http://www.sfwa.org/org/voluntrs.htm |date=September 24, 2006 }}</ref> and chaired the novel jury in 2008.<ref>{{cite web | title = About the Awards Committee and Nebula Juries | work = Nebula Awards | publisher = SFWA | year = 2009 | url = http://www.nebulaawards.com/index.php/about/committee | access-date = 2009-03-22 | archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6ARJTSPCU?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080830124334/http://www.nebulaawards.com/index.php/about/committee | archive-date = September 5, 2012 | url-status = dead | df =  }}</ref> In 2005, Silver was one of the co-ordinators of the Nebula weekend in [[Chicago]].<ref>[http://www.sfwa.org/awards/2005/Staff.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070103081358/http://www.sfwa.org/awards/2005/Staff.html |date=January 3, 2007 }}</ref> In 2008, he was appointed SFWA Event Coordinator and has helped run the Nebula Award Weekends in that capacity since 2009.<ref>Nebula Award Weekend 2012 Guide.</ref>\n\n===Fanzines===\nSilver is known as an on-line reviewer and has written several articles for [[science fiction fanzine]]s, as well as publishing his own annual fanzine ''[[Argentus]]'', which was nominated for a [[Hugo Award for Best Fanzine]] in 2008, 2009, and 2010,<ref name=\"Locus\" /> and won the Chronic Rift Roundtable Award for Best Fanzine in 2009<ref>{{cite web | last = Hawkins | first = Kit | title = The Chronic Rift's 2009 Roundtable Award Winners | work = SF Scope | publisher = SFScope.com | date = 2009-04-08 | url = http://sfscope.com/2009/04/the-chronic-rifts-2009-roundta.html | access-date = 2011-07-12 | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101221072448/http://sfscope.com/2009/04/the-chronic-rifts-2009-roundta.html | archive-date = 2010-12-21 | df =  }}</ref> and the monthly [[Amateur press association|APA]]-zine ''Plata''. He has guest edited two issues of ''[[Journey Planet]]''.\n\n===Conventions===\nIn addition to his writing and editing activities, Silver is involved in running [[science fiction convention]]s. He has chaired [[Windycon]] twice,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isfic.org/conspast.asp |title=ISFiC, Inc.: Windycons Past |publisher=Isfic.org |date= |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref> founded Midfan and chaired the first Midwest Construction, and ran programming for [[58th World Science Fiction Convention|Chicon 2000]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicon.org/ |title=Chicon 7: The 70th World Science Fiction Convention |publisher=Chicon.org |date=2012-09-03 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref> the [[Worldcon]]. From 1998 through 2006 and again from 2008, he sat on the board of directors for [[ISFiC]]. He served as a vice chair for [[70th World Science Fiction Convention|Chicon 7]] in 2012.\n\n==Personal background==\nIn 2000, Silver appeared on ''[[Jeopardy!]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.techwr-l.com/techwhirl/archives/0006/techwhirl-0006-00814.html |title=OT - Tech writer on Jeopardy |publisher=Techwr-l.com |date=2000-06-16 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref> winning two days and coming in second on his third day. He won $15,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.bluegrass.net/~megsmath/jeopardy/jeopardy5.html |title=How I got on Jeopardy! |publisher=Home.bluegrass.net |date= |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website |www.sfsite.com/~silverag}}\n* {{isfdb name|11033|name=Steven H Silver}}\n* {{LCAuth|nr2003013476|Steven H Silver|4|}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Silver, Steven H}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alternate history fandom]]\n[[Category:Indiana University alumni]]\n[[Category:Jeopardy! contestants]]\n[[Category:Science fiction fans]]\n[[Category:American alternate history writers]]\n[[Category:American fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:American science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Science fiction editors]]\n[[Category:People from Hinsdale, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Male speculative fiction editors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| image          = Steven_H_Silver.jpg\n| image_size     = 150px |\n| caption        = Silver in 2008\n| subject name   = Steven H Silver\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1967|4|19}}\n| birth_place    = [[Hinsdale, Illinois]], United States \n| occupation     = [[Technical writer]], [[editing|editor]], [[publisher]], [[reviewer]], bid proposal writer\n}}\n'''Steven H <!-- no punctuation point after the \"H\" -->Silver''' (born April 19, 1967 in [[Hinsdale, Illinois]]) is an [[United States|American]] [[science fiction]] [[science fiction fandom|fan]] and [[bibliography|bibliographer]], publisher, author, and [[List of science fiction editors|editor]].  He has been nominated for the [[Hugo Award]] for [[Hugo Award for Best Fan Writer|Best Fan Writer]] twelve times and [[Hugo Award for Best Fanzine|Best Fanzine]] five times without winning.<ref name=\"Locus\">{{cite web|last=Kelly |first=Mark R. |title=Hugo Nominees List |work=Locus Index to SF Awards |publisher=Locus |year=2009 |url=http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/HugoNomList.html |access-date=2009-03-21 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110920202744/http://www.locusmag.com/SFAwards/Db/HugoNomList.html |archive-date=September 20, 2011 }}</ref>\n\n==Editor, publisher, and writer==\nSilver is a longtime contributing editor to [[SF Site]] and has written that site's news page since its inception.\n\nIn 2003, he co-edited three anthologies with [[Martin H. Greenberg]], ''[[Wondrous Beginnings]]'', ''[[Magical Beginnings]]'', and ''[[Horrible Beginnings]]'', which reprinted the first published stories of authors in the [[science fiction]], [[fantasy]], and [[Horror fiction|horror]] genres. From 2004 through 2012 he was the publisher and editor of [[ISFiC Press]].<ref>{{cite web | title = Silver Resigns from ISFiC Press | publisher = SF Site | date = 2012-11-12 | url = http://www.sfsite.com/news/2012/11/12/silver-resigns-from-isfic-press/ | accessdate = 2012-11-16}}</ref>\n\nSilver published his first short story, \"''Les Lettres de Paston''\", in the final issue of ''[[Helix SF]]''.<ref>{{cite journal | last = Silver | first = Steven H | title = Les Lettres de Paston | journal = Helix SF | issue = 10 | date = Fall 2008 | url = http://www.sfsite.com/~silverag/les_lettres_de_paston.htm | accessdate = 2008-10-01}}</ref> Silver had earlier written a column on [[alternate history]] for the magazine.\n\nIn 2009 and 2010, he edited the two volume Selected Stories of [[Lester del Rey]] for [[NESFA Press]].  The first volume is entitled ''War and Space'' and appeared in August, 2009.<ref>{{cite web | title = War and Space by Lester del Rey | publisher = NESFA Press | date = December 12, 2009 | url = http://www.nesfa.org/press/Books/delRey-1.html | accessdate = March 16, 2010}}</ref> The second volume, ''Robots and Magic'' was published in February 2010.<ref>{{cite web | title = Magic and Robots by Lester del Rey | publisher = NESFA Press | date = December 12, 2009 | url = http://www.nesfa.org/press/Books/delRey-2.html | accessdate = March 16, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Fandom==\n\n===Sidewise and Nebula Awards===\nIn 1995, he founded the [[Sidewise Award for Alternate History]] and has served as a judge ever since.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uchronia.net/sidewise/about.html |title=Sidewise: About the Awards |publisher=Uchronia.net |date= |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref> He was on the short story jury for the [[Nebula Award]] in 2002,<ref>''SFWA Forum'', February 2003, p. 10</ref> and on the novel jury for the Nebula Award in 2003,<ref>''SFWA Forum'', April 2003, p. 15</ref> 2006,<ref>[http://www.sfwa.org/org/voluntrs.htm ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060924223240/http://www.sfwa.org/org/voluntrs.htm |date=September 24, 2006 }}</ref> and chaired the novel jury in 2008.<ref>{{cite web | title = About the Awards Committee and Nebula Juries | work = Nebula Awards | publisher = SFWA | year = 2009 | url = http://www.nebulaawards.com/index.php/about/committee | access-date = 2009-03-22 | archive-url = https://www.webcitation.org/6ARJTSPCU?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20080830124334/http://www.nebulaawards.com/index.php/about/committee | archive-date = September 5, 2012 | url-status = dead | df =  }}</ref> In 2005, Silver was one of the co-ordinators of the Nebula weekend in [[Chicago]].<ref>[http://www.sfwa.org/awards/2005/Staff.html ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070103081358/http://www.sfwa.org/awards/2005/Staff.html |date=January 3, 2007 }}</ref> In 2008, he was appointed SFWA Event Coordinator and has helped run the Nebula Award Weekends in that capacity since 2009.<ref>Nebula Award Weekend 2012 Guide.</ref>\n\n===Fanzines===\nSilver is known as an on-line reviewer and has written several articles for [[science fiction fanzine]]s, as well as publishing his own annual fanzine ''[[Argentus]]'', which was nominated for a [[Hugo Award for Best Fanzine]] in 2008, 2009, and 2010,<ref name=\"Locus\" /> and won the Chronic Rift Roundtable Award for Best Fanzine in 2009<ref>{{cite web | last = Hawkins | first = Kit | title = The Chronic Rift's 2009 Roundtable Award Winners | work = SF Scope | publisher = SFScope.com | date = 2009-04-08 | url = http://sfscope.com/2009/04/the-chronic-rifts-2009-roundta.html | access-date = 2011-07-12 | url-status = dead | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20101221072448/http://sfscope.com/2009/04/the-chronic-rifts-2009-roundta.html | archive-date = 2010-12-21 | df =  }}</ref> and the monthly [[Amateur press association|APA]]-zine ''Plata''. He has guest edited two issues of ''[[Journey Planet]]''.\n\n===Conventions===\nIn addition to his writing and editing activities, Silver is involved in running [[science fiction convention]]s. He has chaired [[Windycon]] twice,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.isfic.org/conspast.asp |title=ISFiC, Inc.: Windycons Past |publisher=Isfic.org |date= |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref> founded Midfan and chaired the first Midwest Construction, and ran programming for [[58th World Science Fiction Convention|Chicon 2000]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicon.org/ |title=Chicon 7: The 70th World Science Fiction Convention |publisher=Chicon.org |date=2012-09-03 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref> the [[Worldcon]]. From 1998 through 2006 and again from 2008, he sat on the board of directors for [[ISFiC]]. He served as a vice chair for [[70th World Science Fiction Convention|Chicon 7]] in 2012.\n\n==Personal background==\nIn 2000, Silver appeared on ''[[Jeopardy!]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.techwr-l.com/techwhirl/archives/0006/techwhirl-0006-00814.html |title=OT - Tech writer on Jeopardy |publisher=Techwr-l.com |date=2000-06-16 |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref> winning two days and coming in second on his third day. He won $15,000.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://home.bluegrass.net/~megsmath/jeopardy/jeopardy5.html |title=How I got on Jeopardy! |publisher=Home.bluegrass.net |date= |accessdate=2015-07-22}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{official website |www.sfsite.com/~silverag}}\n* {{isfdb name|11033|name=Steven H Silver}}\n* {{LCAuth|nr2003013476|Steven H Silver|4|}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Silver, Steven H}}\n[[Category:1967 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alternate history fandom]]\n[[Category:Indiana University alumni]]\n[[Category:Jeopardy! contestants]]\n[[Category:Science fiction fans]]\n[[Category:American alternate history writers]]\n[[Category:American fantasy writers]]\n[[Category:American science fiction writers]]\n[[Category:Science fiction editors]]\n[[Category:People from Hinsdale, Illinois]]\n[[Category:Male speculative fiction editors]]\n", "name_user": "Deb", "label": "safe", "comment": "bring intro into line with bio standards", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Steven_H_Silver"}
